The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | Fresh rate cuts on way 
                                                                                                               Fresh rate cuts on way 
          OUR CORRESPONDENT                          Chandrasekhar: Upbeat                                  
	New Delhi, April 2: State-run banks are likely to slash their benchmark prime lending rates by 50-100 basis points after the government today expressed concern over costly loans despite the RBI incentives. The government is targeting a 24 per cent credit growth this fiscal to revive a slowing economy.        
	At a meeting on the credit situation, cabinet secretary K. M. Chandrasekhar asked state-run banks to review their lending rates as some sectors were facing a shortage of loans.        
	We are in a situation where all of us have to work together and we have to see to what extent we can bring it (interest rate) down together, Chandrasekhar said.        
	The PSU banks have indicated that they would take a call on the interest rates soon, CII director-general Chandrajit Banerjee said.        
	The government also expects private banks to cut rates, industry players present at the meet said.        
	One did so today  Axis Bank. It reduced its benchmark prime lending rate by 50 basis points to 15.25 per cent.        
	Chandrasekhar said state-run banks had stepped up lending and a growth rate of about 24 per cent in credit is anticipated this year. Bank loans were up 18 per cent by early March year-on-year, RBI data showed.        
	At the meeting today, a committee was set up comprising representatives from the government, the Reserve Bank, PSU banks and industry to look into sectoral credit flow, restructuring of loans and procedural issues.                                                                                                                                        
